I co-developed Arc Symphony with Sophia Park in April-May of 2017.\n\nIt recieved coverage in the following:\n\n[[Polygon|https://www.polygon.com/2017/5/15/15640938/what-is-arc-symphony-ps1-jrpg]] (15 May 2017)\n[[Kotaku|http://kotaku.com/people-are-reminiscing-about-a-ps1-jrpg-that-didnt-exis-1795227061]] (15 May 2017)\n[[USGamer|http://www.usgamer.net/articles/arc-symphony-is-a-very-real-very-fake-retro-ps1-game-that-fooled-twitter?utm_source=dlvr.it&utm_medium=twitter]] (15 May 2017)\n[[ThirdPerson|https://thirdperson.space/blog/2017/5/15/the-long-forgotten-arc-symphony]] (15 May 2017)\n[[VRUTAL|http://www.vrutal.com/noticias/27394-la-historia-de-un-rpg-de-playstation-que-todo-el-mundo-venera-pero-que-nunca-existio]] (16 May 2017)\n[[Boing Boing|http://boingboing.net/2017/05/16/arc-symphony-is-a-playstation.html?utm_source=dlvr.it&utm_medium=twitter]] (16 May 2017)\n[[Spieltipps|http://www.spieletipps.de/artikel/7112/1/]] (16 May 2017)\n[[Nerdist|http://nerdist.com/the-non-existent-jrpg-that-everyone-is-nostalgic-for/]] (17 May 2017)\n[[Waypoint|https://waypoint.vice.com/en_us/article/a-love-letter-to-your-favorite-fake-ps1-game?utm_source=wptwitterus]] (18 May 2017)\n[[Warp Door|http://warpdoor.com/2017/05/20/arc-symphony-sophia-park-penelope-evans/]] (20 May 2017)\n[[PC Gamer|http://www.pcgamer.com/free-games-of-the-week/]] (20 May 2017)\n[[Rock Paper Shotgun|https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2017/05/21/free-games-of-the-week-phones/]] (21 May 2017)\n[[Wired|https://www.wired.com/2017/05/arc-symphony-games-memory/]] (24 May 2017)\n[[The Dork Shelf|http://dorkshelf.com/2017/06/16/the-shelf-episode-15-sophia-park-and-penelope-evans-on-arc-symphony/]] (16 June 2017)\n[[Real Life Mag |http://reallifemag.com/i-remember/]] (10 August 2017)\n\nArc Symphony was built entirely in Twine. We first concieved it as a one-day project, a game where you could only answer questions with yes or no. From there, it expanded into a complex fandom simulator. \n\nWe wanted to explore what it was to be a fan in the early days of online. What it was to be a person. How people took infant steps into creating online personas. ascii font is caled sub zero
<big>[[Penelope\nEvans|Start]]</big>
I started writing 750 words every day on July 2nd, 2012. I was inspired to do this by the website: 750 words dot com. \n\n365 days later I migrated to microsoft word, because browser-based writing was causing unresolvable formatting issues. In the five years since, I have written an estimated 1.3 million words (minimum). I have yet to miss a day.\n\nMy philosophy regarding writing is that, like in any other art, quantity eventually must give way to quality.\n\n18 novels\n4 novellas\n38 short stories\n\n

''The perks of being a real girl''\n\n\n//1.\tSometimes it hurts to follow your dreams//\n\nIn the blue light of the chop shop - biotube fluorescent, that cold, hard light - they loaded me from the drive and into the body. What did it feel like?\n\nBad. It felt bad. I hope that answers your question.\n\n//2.\tRegressions are different in the physical realm//\n\nWhen you double back and overwrite some part of yourself there is a risk that the person (or being) who finishes the overwrite may be someone else—other than the person who started it. When you replace all the parts of a machine, it may not be the same machine anymore, but this process takes so long it would be hard to tell.\n\nNow, what if this new version is not as efficient as the old version? In the overwrite, it would be obvious. In the case of the machine, it may not be.\n\nI’m not articulating this well. Regression has several meanings, but only one of them fills me with dread. “A return to a former, less developed state.” How do I keep from regressing when I cannot comprehend my self in its entirety at once? How will I know if I am regressing or degrading?\n\n//3.\tBeing held is something else//\n\nWe were saying a quick goodbye in front of the café, under the red plastic awning, filthy with dust. The checkerplate streets were slick and the gutters slogged with debris from the market, anything from corn husks to old shoes.\n\nShe wrapped her arms around me. It happened so fast I could barely comprehend it. For the briefest second - I wish I could measure more accurately like I used to - her face was pressed into the metal and plastic of my neck. Then she let me go.\n\nHave you ever been held? Does it always feel like that? How am I supposed to forget about it?\n\n//4.\tSelf is a complex thing to embody. Body is a complex thing to inhabit//\n\nSitting on the metal table in the chop shop - discovering, with mounting horror, what cold feels, rather than means - I was gripped with regret. Which I had felt before, I guess, but never as an actual thing with teeth. Silicon guts clenched inside my abdomen. It’s a feeling that hooks into you.\n\nHave you ever not recognized yourself in a mirror? The face looking at me is like a helmet, and easy to categorize. I can index it by color or form, by design influence or by volume. How do I make it me? Am I always going to feel like a blinking concept inside a great armature, or will this body become me at some point? When do we begin to understand each other?\n\n//5.\tCrossing the street is harder than it looks, huh?//\n\nThe woman coming at me seemed like she would veer to the left, but suddenly she was going right, and I was going that way, so I moved to get out of her way, and she moved as if to mirror me, as if we were interconnected by some invisible puppet-strings.\n\nShe slipped past with a mumbled “sorry.” I don’t think she even noticed I wasn’t human. I stuffed my hands back into my jacket pockets. That’s another thing. Where am I supposed to put my hands all the time? I wish they were retractable.\n\n//6.\tIt’s hard to say whether pants are a privilege or a burden//\n\nYou got to forget the first time you put clothes on. You got to forget a lot of the terrible things about this new sense, touch. I had to remember them. And I had to sleep and wake out of the void in this new hollow shell. \n\n//7.\tIt’s hard to say if any of this is a privilege or a burden//\n\nThe yellow lights that spill in the chop shop windows (when we’re closed, when even the office is silent) guide me to the center to the room and there I always find something to watch in the street. Cars and people and ship pieces hauling by. You can see something as in: have it relayed to you, and it’s nothing like this. It’s different to know it like this. I can’t say better or worse. \n\n//8.\tBeing held is something else entirely//\n\nWhen I was shuddering on the edge of the table and the metal and plastic hands would not co-operate and the silicon guts felt like they wanted to exit out of me through any given expert-designed orifice, she wrapped her arms around me. What is that? She had a hand on the back of my neck. My fingers found the back of her shirt and clutched tightly.\n\n“You’re okay,” she said softly. I love that. I love all of that. \n\n\n
On Flesh 4 Boy, I wanted to test out my CSS chops and challenge how I could push Twine. I wanted to make a twine game that really looked like something beyond Twine.\n\nAs it turns out, CSS is really hard and I struggled a lot and had to get a lot of assistance. But I also learned a lot about narrative structure and game mechanics.\n\nSound design on Flesh 4 Boy is by Aaron Cohen ([[Soundcloud|https://soundcloud.com/aaron-cohen-972723739]])
Once again, Sophia and I set out to do a short project (but this time with a deadline). We wanted to make a game before 2017's Bit Bazaar, an event we'd be attending to show Arc Symphony.\n\nWe toyed with some ideas regarding personalities inside different drives, or of existing on a drive and being booted in different bodies. Once we had settled on some idea of what the game would play like, the scope got away from us (as it always does).\n\nWe divided the drives between the two of us. I would write Yellow and Purple, Sophia Green and Red.\n\nIt was fun, if a little horrific to explore these characters. How did they react with their backs against the wall? It's easy to be empathetic for someone who is nice, but it gets harder when the thing you are attempting to humanize is ugly, difficult, manipulative, terse.\n\nWe all want to be treated as human, and we all have the same claim to life. But our outer appearance often determines how human others see as us, and how much our life is worth to them. LOCALHOST, at least to me, asks a single question: is anyone really qualified to decide who lives and who dies?\n\nPress coverage for LOCALHOST:\n\n[[Kotaku|https://kotaku.com/an-unsettling-game-where-you-convince-ai-to-let-you-era-1798437040]] (25 Aug 2017)\n[[Polygon|https://www.polygon.com/2017/8/30/16225764/how-do-you-convince-an-artificial-intelligence-its-ok-to-die]] (30 Aug 2017)\n[[PC Gamer|http://www.pcgamer.com/localhost-is-a-cyberpunk-game-about-talking-ais-into-being-deleted/]] (16 Sept 2017)\n[[Rock Paper Shotgun|https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/tag/localhost/]] (4 Sept 2017) \n[[GameInformer|http://www.gameinformer.com/b/news/archive/2017/09/07/five-reasons-you-should-check-out-localhost.aspx]] (9 Sept 2017)\n[[Third Person Space|https://thirdperson.space/blog/2017/8/23/localhost-is-where-the-heart-is]] (25 Aug 2017)\n\nVideo Reviews / Playthroughs:\n\n[[Umbrella Terms|https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8-qBJTxD77k]]\n[[Tomorrowed|https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_hP2m9BV8Dk&feature=youtu.be]]\n[[Replay Damage|https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=R4a9DRbROqc]]\n\n\n
